CHADE MENG TAN:
Two more questions.

00:32:34.130 --> 00:32:38.290
AUDIENCE: Thank you for your
inspiring and interesting talk.

00:32:38.290 --> 00:32:42.770
I cannot see clearly the
difference or they need

00:32:42.770 --> 00:32:52.010
of saying caring mindfulness
and mindfulness because, for me,

00:32:52.010 --> 00:32:55.080
according to my experience
when I practice mindfulness,

00:32:55.080 --> 00:33:02.120
this caring feeling or need to
take care of myself and others

00:33:02.120 --> 00:33:03.560
is born naturally.

00:33:03.560 --> 00:33:04.670
MATTHIEU RICARD: Yes.

00:33:04.670 --> 00:33:06.750
So that's exactly what
Jon Kabat-Zinn said,

00:33:06.750 --> 00:33:08.350
and he's right.

00:33:08.350 --> 00:33:11.000
If you do it properly
with the right instructor

00:33:11.000 --> 00:33:14.090
in the right way, he
says it always witnesses

00:33:14.090 --> 00:33:16.870
a strong opening to others.

00:33:16.870 --> 00:33:18.260
Great.

00:33:18.260 --> 00:33:23.910
But you know, it's still
an expected byproduct.

00:33:23.910 --> 00:33:27.270
And it depends on
how it's taught.

00:33:27.270 --> 00:33:32.610
But again to take the sniper
example, he's mindful.

00:33:32.610 --> 00:33:34.220
No question.

00:33:34.220 --> 00:33:36.430
So he's not caring.

00:33:36.430 --> 00:33:38.630
So you could have that.

00:33:38.630 --> 00:33:42.490
So just to avoid that
and to reinforce that

00:33:42.490 --> 00:33:44.650
among the qualities that
mindfulness should bring,

00:33:44.650 --> 00:33:47.740
caring is one of
the most powerful.

00:33:47.740 --> 00:33:50.010
And actually many
studies have shown,

00:33:50.010 --> 00:33:55.420
like Tania Singer's one year
study, that mindfulness alone

00:33:55.420 --> 00:34:00.162
reduces stress, doesn't
bring prosocial behavior.

00:34:00.162 --> 00:34:02.370
Although the people say
they're actually more caring,

00:34:02.370 --> 00:34:05.370
but in behavior they don't
really make much difference.

00:34:05.370 --> 00:34:07.090
So nothing wrong.

00:34:07.090 --> 00:34:08.630
Nothing to put it down.

00:34:08.630 --> 00:34:11.909
But the scientific results
show that it doesn't per se

00:34:11.909 --> 00:34:14.310
automatically bring about
more prosocial behavior

00:34:14.310 --> 00:34:17.800
while loving kindness
[INAUDIBLE] does in a big way.

00:34:17.800 --> 00:34:19.429
So when those results
are be published,

00:34:19.429 --> 00:34:21.554
I think that we'll also
clarify the situation then.

00:34:21.554 --> 00:34:23.699
Yes, when it's well
done, probably yes.

00:34:23.699 --> 00:34:26.219
But not necessarily with
every instructor, not with

00:34:26.219 --> 00:34:27.620
every practitioner.

00:34:27.620 --> 00:34:30.580
So then why mention
it so clearly

00:34:30.580 --> 00:34:33.060
that you can't escape it?

00:34:33.060 --> 00:34:33.790
Yes.

00:34:33.790 --> 00:34:37.520
And then also you have
a lot of programs,

00:34:37.520 --> 00:34:40.300
like Search Inside
Yourself, the well-being,

00:34:40.300 --> 00:34:43.580
the mindfulness
training, and MBSR, MBCT.

00:34:43.580 --> 00:34:45.969
And a few friends
thought should also

00:34:45.969 --> 00:34:48.471
gather meditation
instruction that

00:34:48.471 --> 00:34:50.929
includes very clearly the notion
of compassionate altruism.

00:34:54.639 --> 00:34:56.219
So there's a trailer
now that will be

00:34:56.219 --> 00:34:58.040
completely online from August.

00:34:58.040 --> 00:35:00.180
It's called "Imagine Clarity."

00:35:00.180 --> 00:35:05.520
And I participate in helping
them to build up those apps

00:35:05.520 --> 00:35:10.240
and among other teachers
to-- I'm not a teacher,

00:35:10.240 --> 00:35:12.470
but to share those instructions.

00:35:12.470 --> 00:35:14.230
And so you can look
at that as well.

00:35:14.230 --> 00:35:18.350
I think already a trailer
on "Imagine Clarity."

00:35:18.350 --> 00:35:20.909
And also to do things
like what Meng is teaching

00:35:20.909 --> 00:35:22.200
with this 10 second meditation.

00:35:22.200 --> 00:35:23.700
I think it's very powerful.

00:35:23.700 --> 00:35:26.810
And one example that I
gave over to Meng to use

00:35:26.810 --> 00:35:29.650
is, why only 10 seconds,
but actually it's

00:35:29.650 --> 00:35:30.850
more than 10 seconds?

00:35:30.850 --> 00:35:34.400
And for example, if you open a
flask of perfume for 10 seconds

00:35:34.400 --> 00:35:37.020
and close it, perfume
still will last longer.

00:35:37.020 --> 00:35:40.030
And if you open it often
enough for 10 seconds,

00:35:40.030 --> 00:35:41.300
it will be there all the time.

00:35:41.300 --> 00:35:43.020
So it's just that we're
setting something in motion.

00:35:43.020 --> 00:35:44.360
It's not just 10
seconds and then

00:35:44.360 --> 00:35:46.318
we go back to bashing
people and slapping them.

00:35:48.232 --> 00:35:50.315
CHADE-MENG TAN: Let me
clarify the 10 second thing

00:35:50.315 --> 00:35:51.874
you're talking about.

00:35:51.874 --> 00:35:54.040
The 10 second exercise that
Matthieu's talking about

00:35:54.040 --> 00:35:56.760
is every now and then
just spend 10 seconds,

00:35:56.760 --> 00:35:58.990
identify two human
beings, and secretly

00:35:58.990 --> 00:36:00.950
wishing for them to be happy.

00:36:00.950 --> 00:36:02.224
So that is very powerful.

00:36:02.224 --> 00:36:04.890
MATTHIEU RICARD: So people can't
say that don't have 10 seconds.

00:36:04.890 --> 00:36:05.883
People maybe don't have time.

00:36:05.883 --> 00:36:06.480
They don't have 20 minutes.

00:36:06.480 --> 00:36:07.105
But 10 seconds?

00:36:07.105 --> 00:36:10.340
Nobody can dare to say
I don't have 10 seconds.

00:36:10.340 --> 00:36:12.520
CHADE-MENG TAN:
The last question.

00:36:12.520 --> 00:36:14.151
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:36:14.151 --> 00:36:17.370
I'm losing things
from my pocket.

00:36:17.370 --> 00:36:22.400
When I first encountered
loving kindness practice,

00:36:22.400 --> 00:36:24.940
it seemed very conceptual--
I wish you joy.

00:36:24.940 --> 00:36:28.670
I wish you peace--
without a feeling quality.

00:36:28.670 --> 00:36:33.380
Sometimes, a real feeling
of warmth is there,

00:36:33.380 --> 00:36:34.360
and I can feel it.

00:36:34.360 --> 00:36:37.490
And when I accompany those
thoughts of may you be happy,

00:36:37.490 --> 00:36:39.920
may you be free from
suffering with that feeling,

00:36:39.920 --> 00:36:41.470
it becomes much more powerful.

00:36:41.470 --> 00:36:43.650
But sometimes that
feeling isn't there

00:36:43.650 --> 00:36:47.100
and I don't know how to generate
it effectively or consistently.

00:36:47.100 --> 00:36:49.432
Do you have any advice for that?

00:36:49.432 --> 00:36:53.160
MATTHIEU RICARD: So I remember
not far from here many years

00:36:53.160 --> 00:36:58.687
ago, I met Paul Ekman, who's
a great scientist on emotion.

00:36:58.687 --> 00:36:59.770
He asked me this question.

00:36:59.770 --> 00:37:01.650
When you feel
compassion, do you have

00:37:01.650 --> 00:37:03.605
to feel the suffering of others?

00:37:03.605 --> 00:37:06.690
At that time, I had
not worked with people

00:37:06.690 --> 00:37:09.690
working on empathy so I was
not sure-- be Sometimes yes,

00:37:09.690 --> 00:37:10.930
sometimes no.

00:37:10.930 --> 00:37:11.560
I was not sure.

00:37:11.560 --> 00:37:15.160
Then we distinguished
nicely empathy, compassion,

00:37:15.160 --> 00:37:16.610
and so forth.

00:37:16.610 --> 00:37:21.310
So in short, when you
think of all the suffering,

00:37:21.310 --> 00:37:25.000
just thinking with empathy,
like those Romanian children.

00:37:25.000 --> 00:37:26.900
There is a strong
emotional component

00:37:26.900 --> 00:37:30.630
that then triggers and
should bring about loving

00:37:30.630 --> 00:37:32.870
kindness and compassion.

00:37:32.870 --> 00:37:35.550
But there's also a
cognitive aspect.

00:37:35.550 --> 00:37:37.140
In Buddhism, we
think that suffering

00:37:37.140 --> 00:37:41.330
is not just headache,
or being tortured,

00:37:41.330 --> 00:37:43.630
or terrible things like
that which are obvious.

00:37:43.630 --> 00:37:45.992
Why did the Buddha teach
of the four noble truths,

00:37:45.992 --> 00:37:47.200
the truth of suffering first?

00:37:47.200 --> 00:37:50.190
We don't need the Buddha to
tell us headaches or toothaches

00:37:50.190 --> 00:37:51.430
are suffering.

00:37:51.430 --> 00:37:52.930
But he meant much
more than that.

00:37:52.930 --> 00:37:55.876
He meant that as long as you
are a man, you're deluded.

00:37:55.876 --> 00:37:57.250
And as long as
you strongly grasp

00:37:57.250 --> 00:38:00.230
the solidity of permanence,
and friends, and enemies,

00:38:00.230 --> 00:38:04.900
and those solidifications of
reality and distorting reality,

00:38:04.900 --> 00:38:06.650
you are bound to suffer.

00:38:06.650 --> 00:38:07.950
This is not very emotional.

00:38:07.950 --> 00:38:11.870
The root is that
distorting reality brings

00:38:11.870 --> 00:38:13.970
hatred, jealousy-- all that.

00:38:13.970 --> 00:38:16.410
So you can, of course,
take compassionate

00:38:16.410 --> 00:38:20.050
about the root of suffering,
but it is not very emotional.

00:38:20.050 --> 00:38:22.990
But you understand the
deep cause of suffering.

00:38:22.990 --> 00:38:28.030
So depending upon times, we have
seen many times the Dalai Lama.

00:38:28.030 --> 00:38:30.070
You're having tears in
the middle of teaching.

00:38:30.070 --> 00:38:32.014
And he said the
last 30 years when

00:38:32.014 --> 00:38:34.180
he does his four hours of
meditation in the morning,

00:38:34.180 --> 00:38:37.030
there's hardly any morning where
I didn't have tears thinking

00:38:37.030 --> 00:38:38.320
of the suffering of beings.

00:38:38.320 --> 00:38:41.500
So you could say it's
emotional, but also he meditates

00:38:41.500 --> 00:38:45.030
on the lack of solid reality.

00:38:45.030 --> 00:38:47.340
And I'm sure it's tears
that come at that time.

00:38:47.340 --> 00:38:50.780
It's understanding wisdom
that reinforces and deepens

00:38:50.780 --> 00:38:52.230
his compassion.

00:38:52.230 --> 00:38:57.160
So those two-- it doesn't have
to be always the emotional.

00:38:57.160 --> 00:38:59.345
There's this cognitive
dimension that

00:38:59.345 --> 00:39:01.410
is very important,
especially in Buddhism,

00:39:01.410 --> 00:39:03.344
but I think in
general, because you

00:39:03.344 --> 00:39:04.510
go at the root of suffering.

00:39:07.057 --> 00:39:09.140
CHADE-MENG TAN: Thank you
so much, my dear friend,

00:39:09.140 --> 00:39:13.260
for benefiting us, for
teaching, and for being a life

00:39:13.260 --> 00:39:14.035
in this world.

00:39:14.035 --> 00:39:15.035
Thank you.

00:39:15.035 --> 00:39:17.530
MATTHIEU RICARD: We'll
see how long it lasts.

